04013nam a22006615i 9780292772069DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20211971txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927720697 a10.7560/7014652doi  a(DE-B1597)587825  a(OCoLC)1286808388  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aJL2661b.A67 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a328.83  aMI 855802rvk1 aAgor, Weston H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Chilean Senate :bInternal Distribution of Influence /cWeston H. Agor. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1971  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLLILAS Latin American Monograph Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWeston Agor’s carefully documented analysis of the organization and workings of the Chilean Senate is the first of its kind and fills a long-standing need in the comparative study of the internal structure of legislative bodies. Making eclectic use of role, power, and exchange theories, Agor bases his discussion on personal interviews with senators and staff as well as on extensive observation of the Senate in action during 1967–1968. He also analyzes in detail relevant documents, committee reports, and floor debates. Focused primarily on the formal decision-making structure within the Senate and on internal norms, both formal and informal, that hold that structure together, Agor’s study fruitfully compares the Chilean Senate with its peers, including the United States Senate, to which it bears surprising resemblance in form and function. Agor examines the role of compromise and informal rules of the game in achieving a majority vote in the Senate, the power of committees and committee presidents, and political party control over Senate members. The influence of the executive, particularly in the passage of executive legislation, and its effect on the Senate’s internal system of checks and balances—both stated and understood—are examined in terms of their effect on the political strength of the Senate. The Chilean Senate, unlike its counterparts in most other “developing countries,” has exercised genuine and effective influence in the national political system. In an epilogue to this study, Agor views events since 1968, including the election of Allende, that affected the future role of the Senate in Chilean politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChile.--Congreso Nacional.--Senado. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311074535140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70146540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292772069423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292772069/original  a978-3-11-074535-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK